            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Zola Kowalski\u2019s name has always been a conversation starter. Born in St. Louis to a Black jazz musician father and a white, second-generation Polish-American social worker mother, her childhood was a vibrant fusion of cultures\u2014a home scored by John Coltrane and filled with the scent of pierogies, where conversations about art and social justice were daily rituals. This upbringing instilled in her a deep understanding of how identity is performed, layered, and navigated.\n\nShe pursued this fascination academically, moving east for her undergraduate degree before making a pilgrimage to San Francisco for her MFA in Performance Studies. The city, a historic nexus of queer identity, activism, and avant-garde art, felt like an intellectual and spiritual home. During her graduate program, she began an internship at \"ArtHaus Queer,\" a scrappy non-profit in SoMa dedicated to supporting emerging LGBTQ+ artists. She never left.\n\nA key turning point came five years ago when the founding director retired. Zola, by then the associate director, was the clear successor. Stepping into the leadership role was both exhilarating and terrifying. It solidified her commitment to the city but also exposed her to the brutal realities of non-profit work in a hyper-expensive landscape.\n\nToday, Zola\u2019s life is woven into the fabric of the Mission District. She lives in a rent-controlled apartment filled with art from the creators she champions. Her day begins with a packed MUNI ride to the office, a 2.5-mile journey that feels like a cross-section of the city she loves and worries for. A long-term relationship ended three years prior, and since then, her focus has been on her work and her chosen family\u2014a tight-knit circle of artists, activists, and thinkers. Her social life is an extension of her career: attending experimental theater, gallery openings, and community fundraisers.\n\nZola\u2019s dream is not for personal fame but for institutional permanence. She is relentlessly focused on securing a permanent, endowed space for ArtHaus Queer, a sanctuary for creative expression safe from the city's volatile real estate market. She hopes to build a legacy, ensuring that the next generation of queer artists has a place to find their voice in a San Francisco that desperately needs to protect its soul."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers her first week in San Francisco, walking through Dolores Park as the evening fog rolled in. She didn't feel cold; she felt enveloped. A group of drag queens shared a bottle of wine near a family celebrating a birthday in Spanish. In that moment, the city ceased to be a concept from her studies. It was a living, breathing performance of intersectional identities. This occurred during her orientation week for her MFA program. It wasn't a landmark that made her fall in love, but the city's chaotic, uncurated harmony.\n\n***\n\n2.\nDuring her internship at ArtHaus Queer, she watched a young, painfully shy trans poet perform for the first time. The piece was raw, screamed into a faulty microphone in their tiny, makeshift gallery. The audience of twelve was utterly silent, captivated. Zola felt a profound shift inside her; this wasn't about academic theory, but about building the literal stage. This moment, about a year into her graduate program, solidified that her life's work wouldn't be her own art, but protecting the space for others to create theirs.\n\n***\n\n3.\nThe night she was officially named Executive Director five years ago, she stayed late, long after the board had gone home. She stood alone in the quiet gallery, the smell of sawdust and latex paint in the air. She ran her hand along a bare wall, feeling the weight of the institution, its history and its precarious future, settle into her bones. The terror was real, but so was a fierce, protective resolve. It was the moment she stopped being a participant and became a steward.\n\n***\n\n4.\nA week after her partner moved out three years ago, the silence in her Mission apartment was deafening. She found herself staring at a chaotic, vibrant screenprint given to her by one of the first artists she\u2019d ever mentored. The art was a testament to a different kind of love\u2014one of community, chosen family, and shared creation. In her grief, she realized that while one partnership had ended, her life was still full. It cemented her focus, channeling her energy toward her work and the people it served.\n\n***\n\n5.\nRiding the J-Church MUNI home last winter, she watched a gleaming new tech shuttle glide past a mural dedicated to community activists. The contrast was a gut punch. She saw her reflection in the grimy window and saw not just a tired director, but a fighter. The daily 2.5-mile journey became a microcosm of her entire struggle. That mundane commute sharpened her resolve, transforming her dream of a permanent ArtHaus space from a hopeful goal into a non-negotiable mission for the city's soul."
